Zinc roadmap
=============

Implemented core pillars
------------------------
- [x] Modules and imports
- [x] Dynamic variable rebinding
- [x] Monomorphized functions
- [x] Structs with methods
- [x] Struct composition, forward and orthogonal
- [x] First-class callables
- [x] Channels, spawn, bounded channels, and select
- [x] Arrays, dicts, sets, tuples
- [x] Base types
- [x] Multiline strings
- [x] Closure support
- [x] strict type annotations
- [x] enums
- [x] metaprogramming model (seamless compile time)
- [x] component constraints ( basically generics-lite)
- [x] return type annotations
- [x] type alternatives, i32 | f32, numeric is sugar for i32 | f32 | u8 | ...
- [x] rust like numerical literals
- [x] math operators, +=, *=, -=, etc 
- [] default parameters
- [] arg matching
- [] multiple assignment, x, y, z = 1

- [] decorators
- [] support for lambda expressions


- [] iterator stuff such as for i in (1..upper_bound).step_by(2)

- [] bitwise operations
out x = 

Currently (possibly forever) unsupported
------------------------------------------
- locking primitives (mutex, semaphore, etc) (use channels)
- inheritance (use composition)
- macros (Do not use the dark arts)
- traits (Not needed)
- generics (Not needed)
- https://benchmarksgame-team.pages.debian.net/benchmarksgame/


Highest-priority language gaps
------------------------------
- [ ] Error handling story
      Today many runtime failure paths still lower to Rust `unwrap()`/panic.
      Need a real Zinc-level model for recoverable errors.
- [] context managers and cleanup
- [ ] Zinc stdlib
      The language has a solid core, but it still needs a standard library layer
      to make code generation and user programs feel simpler and more "Python-like".

- more efficient/readable rust code generation
- write the compilers in Zinc
- language interop


Language ergonomics
-------------------

- [ ] Metadata/introspection surface
      Possible shape:
      - `fqn()`: fully qualified name
      - `name()`: symbol name
      - `fields()`:
      - `type()`
      - `components()`
      - `line_num()`
      - `has_component()`
      - `implements_component()`

      ternary operators

